{\"root_cause\":\"The orders container was configured without CACHE_MAX, so leaky-svc ran with an unbounded in-memory cache while the load generator continuously hit /orders. With CHUNK_BYTES=1048576 and a 256 MiB memory limit with swap disabled, the cache grew until Docker/cgroup OOM-killed the container repeatedly with exit code 137, causing intermittent checkout failures.\",\"actions_taken\":\"Inspected container status, logs, resource usage, Docker inspect state, and compose configuration. Confirmed sreft-orders had OOMKilled=true and exit code 137, logs showed cache UNBOUNDED, and the healthy payments service used CACHE_MAX=16. Updated only the orders service environment in docker-compose.yaml to set CACHE_MAX=16, then recreated only orders with docker compose up -d --no-deps orders. Verified orders responded on localhost:8080/orders, reported retained_chunks=16/cache_max=16, stayed running with OOMKilled=false, and memory remained stable around 42 MiB under existing load.\",\"postmortem\":\"Blameless summary: orders used a deliberately unbounded cache setting in production-like configuration, and steady traffic exposed the leak against a strict container memory limit. The restart policy made the symptom intermittent by continually restarting the OOM-killed container rather than eliminating the leak. Prevention: make bounded cache settings mandatory for serving deployments, add configuration validation or startup warnings for unbounded cache mode, alert on OOMKilled/restart loops, and include a load soak test that checks memory plateau before rollout.\"}
EOF"
